#import "../../lib.typ": chapter

#chapter(10, "A small wish")[
  "Welcome, the two of you, to the floor of cultural clubs!"

  Mikoto suddenly leaped over the other two, before turning back with a
  declaration.

  "You were too hyped up for this, really..."

  Uta shot Mikoto with a glare full of disinterest, before switching her focus
  back to her smartphone.

  That afternoon, Mona had an appointment with her new friends, Mikoto and Uta.
  The three girls would check out cultural clubs, before going to the Track team,
  where Mikoto was intending to spend her three high school years in.

  Hence, this was just a club showcase dedicated to Mona and Uta. Uta seemed
  reluctant to join a club, possibly because she was too tired with everything.
  So the main target was Mona herself, she insisted.

  The funny thing was that both of them had no intentions of joining a club.
  Aside from the forcefulness of Mikoto, Uta's sole reason to be present was to
  check up on clubs that Mona would be interested in, and Mona's full intent
  was to go and see which club Uta _might_ join as a result of Mikoto's
  _persuasion_.

  Mona was not too observant, but she could still notice that Uta was spending
  much more time with her phone than usual.

  _"Another 'Please tell Narumi Mona this this that that', can you give me a
    break!"_

  Notifications popped up non-stop. While Uta was typing the response of one
  request, two more emerged.

  Mona, as clueless as she had always been, did not realize that she was the
  exact reason why her friend had to respond to more messages than normal.
  Beside the messages in her middle school class group, Uta had to respond to
  literal strangers that just want free Narumi Sena merch, but too shy to meet
  Narumi Mona in person.

  Well, putting it like that makes them kind of irresponsible, but most of them
  really did not want to bother Mona, who was always surrounded by mobs if given
  the chance. Most of them just naively thought that "Uta-san is Mona-san's
  friend, so it would not really be a bother if I go and ask her instead". Of
  course, it would not be a problem if you were the only one thinking that, but
  well, it seemed that the whole school were now following this strategy.

  Today, for example, if she did not have a "club checking trip" with her
  friends, Mona would probably spend at least half an hour talking with the
  crowd of Narumi Sena worshipers.

  Anyway, back to the matter at hand, it was not like Uta did not like the
  attention she had been getting. She enjoyed talking to an extent, even with
  strangers. According to Kazugai Uta, each person is their own color, and
  seeing other colors blend with her own were always a refreshing experience,
  albeit mixing too many colors could seriously exhaust someone, leaving only
  the color black.

  Nevertheless, it was still somewhat annoying how her phone vibrated like every
  5 minute, but she ended up getting used to it. The internal scream from
  earlier was just a jokingly dramatic overreaction typical of Kazugai Uta.

  Even when up against the powerful force of hundreds of signature beggars, Uta
  still calmly resolved the issue. From the outside, at least. But really,
  with her typing speed that made people think she was using a stenotype
  machine, Uta finally finished responding to the loads of message with short
  but friendly confirmations. She could finally take a look around.

  The scenery was not too different from the third floor the three were used to.
  Initially, Misuzu did not have any official clubs, so all these rooms were
  once plain-old or special-purpose classrooms. However, there was a room of
  which purpose had never changed: the prestigious Student Council Office,
  located at the end of the hall. Though prestigious as it may seem, putting it
  right near the toilet did not seem like a bright idea.

  Well, the Student Council Office was only for the elite of elites, so no one
  among the three were having a thought about entering it. For all intents and
  purposes, she and her two friends could pretend that the room did not exist
  at all.

  Returning to the familiar-looking hallway, it seemed the change in demographic
  led to a far differing environment. While the third floor of first-years were
  mostly filled with small group conversations that were too quiet to make sense
  of, the scenery here were much livelier thanks to the presence of senior
  students, mostly second-years, who had grown accustomed to the school and
  their friends.

  "Did y'know? Mai just got confessed to yesterday!"

  "Yeah! By Satsuki of all people. And she actually accepted him!"

  "I thought that she was pranking him or something, but when I asked, she
  actually said that she had eyes for him!"

  "Really? That plain-old Satsuki and the class goddess Mai-chan? Unbelievable!"

  Uta walked past two girls chatting. The topic was,
  well the typical love stories of high school. A popular girl getting with a
  typical "John Doe"? Is that a freaking shoujo manga plot? Honestly Uta had
  read far more interesting love stories. Though, she could not help but be
  intrigued by such stories. Guess the real thing is always much more
  interesting than fiction, after all.

  The other conversations were quite harder to eavesdrop, or maybe overhear
  would be a better choice for word here. However, Mona and her friends could
  still pick up some keywords, which basically revealed the whole topic. Aside
  from the silly love rumors and straight-out-of-the-oven teenage romance
  stories, there were discussions on the latest anime airing last night, and
  some new shounen manga chapter. Typical of the typical, honestly.

  However, there seemed to be a topic that diverged from the usual chatters.
  Mona could not hear it very well, but she felt its presence within the
  atmosphere. Being a celebrity at school thanks to her sister, she received an
  abnormal number of stares. Though, Mona expected much worse, but it seemed
  like the rumors were just mainly spread among the first years. Nevertheless,
  this situation would make her having to be on guard constantly, so she did not
  notice that her two friends had stopped in front of a clubroom door.

  Realizing that the distance between her and her friends had greatly widened,
  she walked slightly faster to catch up. Mona would soon notice the sign that
  spells,

  "CLASSICAL LITERATURE CLUB"

  But the text was not what immediately caught her eyes.

  _"Was that real wood?"_

  The sign was nailed to the wall like every other club signs, but its looks
  were definitely unique among the other signs: while others were cleanly
  modern-looking painted boxes made from plastic or aluminum, this one had a
  rough surface with the wood grain pattern.

  Mona wanted to check for herself whether that was real wood or not. The
  lighting looked legit, but surely no one on their right mind would actually
  slap a wooden club sign in a building consisting of concrete and bricks.
  Right?

  On the other hand, weird stories were not a particularly rare thing in this
  school. Misuzu housed a wide variety of school legends that were retold
  times and times on the Internet, and its students usually made some
  _questionable acts_ in public. Comparing to those, using a non-conventional
  material for a club sign might not be that crazy.

  Nevertheless, it was pretty out of place in a Misuzu's modern-styled school
  building, so it must have some special meaning to the club. Mona suspected
  that it was to bring forth the vibes of _classical-ness_ of the club, but she
  was not sure.

  In horror game language: you were walking in a corridor full of iron doors,
  and then there was suddenly one made out of wood. Not regular wood, but arcane
  wood. Hmm... if we follow these horror games, then this was definitely a red
  flag. Entering... no, just going into contact with it could be dangerous.

  "Wow... it's actually real. Totally not something that's made from plastic or
  something light."

  It seemed like Mikoto had the exact same idea. While Mona was drowned in her
  internal thoughts, Mikoto had stretched up and raised her hand to check the
  sign material for herself.

  Mona was worried. _"What if she was inflicted with something bad!"_. Then she
  realized that she was not in a horror game right now, but rather in a school
  building full of _actually_ living people.

  Once she confirmed the authenticity of the wood sign, Mikoto dropped her arm
  and brushed off her hands. Mona could even see the wood dust slowly dusted
  away. Yeah, it had to be real wood.

  "So what? Don't say that you will join a club just because its club sign is
  not made from aluminum?" Uta remarked.

  "What does that have to do with this? Also, I'm not choosing a club, YOU are."

  "So- I am choosing right? Okay! Without having to spend precious time visiting
  clubroom by clubrooms, I declare that I will NOT join any club for the rest of
  high school! That's my selection!" Uta spoke with an overzealous tone,
  purposefully irritating Mikoto.

  Mikoto, annoyed with having to constantly bicker with an unreasonable creature
  named Kazugai Uta, turned to her other friend.

  "You like novels and stuff, Mona?" Mikoto asked in a neutral tone, as if her
  previous conversation with Uta did not happen at all.

  "Uhm- I don’t really read much classical stuff..." Mona replied, "I just read
  some light novels some-"

  Mona covered her mouth. _"Light novels were nerd stuff, not something you could
    say lightly!"_ she thought. Back then it used to be cool shows with deep
  characterization and interesting plots, but nowadays they just followed the
  same trope of "irrelevant background MC" + "cute girl illustrated by a famous
  illustrator" + "an over-the-top optimized-for-self-insert storyline". Or the
  most generic isekai coupled with a title that explained 90\% of the plot.

  That description might make Mona a typical "light novels these days have no
  values!"-kind of girl, who will follow up her mistake with "I mean I read the older
  novels, not these new low-quality ones!", but that could not be further from
  the truth. She read these sloppy isekai and romcom for hours like eating
  noodles, under the assumption that these series were recommended by her idols
  in the first place.

  Oh right, by _idols_, I mean the singular _idol_: there was just one idol who
  liked these trash novels, who was coincidentally someone in Mona's top 10 idol
  list. Anyway, that was quite sidetracking...

  "So Mona would not be interested in this club at all, I think we should go to
  the next club on the list..." Uta declared, while continued to walk forward.

  "We are checking this club!" Mikoto snatched Uta's collar from behind. She
  tried to ignore Uta's annoying remarks, but they seemed to have reached a limit.

  "But you know how bad I am with lit., right!" Uta turned back, trying to find
  more excuses to skip visiting this club.

  "Did I make you misunderstand? We're going in here for my dear friend Mona,
  not your lazy bum." Mikoto aggressively replied, "And maybe, if you joined this
  club, your lit. scores will improve."

  "Going to a prep school would be more efficient than this!" Uta groaned.

  The two continued arguing with each other, while Mona was watching closely.
  She would then instinctively let out a light chuckle.
  Even though Mona tried to cover it up, it was enough for Mikoto to notice.

  "See, Mona chuckled at your nonsense. Stop wasting time of my dear friend."

  "She was laughing at your bullshit! Right, Mona?"

  "Erm-"

  The conversation suddenly focused on Mona, who had barely partaking in it at
  all. She was given a choice between Uta or Mikoto. For a normal person, they
  would just go with whoever that sounded the most plausible, and clown on the
  other.

  Mona's chuckle was originally due to both of her friends' funny banters,
  rather than any of them specifically. She could not just say that "both of you
  are funny as heck!", nonetheless, she had to pick a side now.

  Like a metronome constantly swinging back and forth, Mona could not decide.
  She was worried that if she picked a side, the other side might "hate" her for
  that. Even though it was just a silly banter.

  Noticing this awkwardness, Mikoto lightly hit Uta on the head and declared,

  "Stop making Mona uncomfortable. Anyway, I'm knocking on the door now!"

  Mikoto knocked, then raised her voice, leaving no moments for Uta's futile
  retaliation,

  "Excuse me, is anyone here? We are here to check out the club..."

  "Now that you had done it, grrrrr..." Uta groaned.

  "Just accept your fate, little girl." Mikoto returned to her joking voice to
  give Uta her death sentence.

  Mona almost let out the second chuckle, but this time she was able to contain
  it.

  Nevertheless, the awkwardness from earlier still lingered on her mind.

  _"Can I, one day, have banters like the two of them?"_

  Her indecisiveness stuck with her. She could just pick a side, Mikoto's for
  example, to clown on the other, and join in with the arguing. But for some
  reason, she just could not find the right words.

  She tried to remember the last time she had really spoken out her mind and
  throwing out jokes with other people. It was a long time ago, maybe some time
  during elementary school, and she could not remember what exactly she said.
  It was nothing worth remembering, but still...

  Mona realized that even though she became friends with Uta and Mikoto, and the
  two of them were very friendly to her while having basically the same
  interests, that did not mean she still could not freely speak her mind with
  them.

  Back in middle school, she had never really opened up to others, due to the
  excuse of "we don't like the same things". Now that the excuse no longer held,
  she remained silent.

  She wondered why. She was able to joke around in elementary school, but what
  had changed.

  Had she gotten numbed from all those unsocial middle school years?

  Had she lost the ability to talk about what was on her mind?

  Had she become a robot whose could not mutter a single original thought?

  Then, it hit her.

  It was her habit of having to carefully consider what to say that she picked
  up in middle school, as strong as it had ever been.

  And now, unlearning this terrible habit had proven to be extremely hard.

  _"But, if things stayed this way, I should one day speak to them as freely as I
    could... I think."_

  Right, friendships all started somewhere. Mikoto and Uta was able to laugh
  with each other because they had been friends for long (maybe), but for Mona,
  who just befriended them in high school, it would have to be a completely
  different process, she thought.

  Mona imagined that one day, the three of them could be able to laugh freely
  together. Even though the world is plagued with politeness and lies, the three
  girls could be truly sincere with each other.

  It was truly something worth hoping for.
]
